        ¶

        I stand at the boundary feeling unmoored.

        Brightbloom said, "First time's always hard — saying goodbye to guides."

        Streamwalker said, "You'll say goodbye to us in three days too. That's how this works. Temporary teams for each territory."

        I say, "I know." I wipe my face. "It's just — they were good. Really good."

        Brightbloom said, "Leafwhisper and Rootwalker are excellent — we've worked boundary transfers with them for years. Complementary styles, very effective partnership."

        Streamwalker said, "They spoke highly of you in the coordination documentation — said you ask good questions and adapt quickly. That's valuable on long journeys."

        I manage a smile. I say, "Leafwhisper would say 'excellent adaptation capacity' — and then explain the biological mechanisms for twenty minutes."

        Brightbloom laughed — a bright chiming sound. "That's absolutely accurate! Leafwhisper loves explaining things!"

        Streamwalker said, "And Rootwalker would say 'walks good'."

        I say, "Exactly."

        There is a pause. The boundary clearing feels liminal — between territories, between teams, between what is and what will be.

        Streamwalker asked, "Ready to keep going?"

        I look back once more at the forest — Territory One, where I'd learned to walk all day, to see forests as networks, to trust guides who communicated through cascade and silence. Then forward to Territory Two — rivers and wetlands, new terrain, new guides, new challenges. The journey continues.

        I say, "Yeah. I'm ready."

        Scout bounces agreement.

        Brightbloom said, "*Excellent!* Let's walk — we've got about two hours before the first river crossing. Very exciting — you'll love the wetlands. Completely different ecosystem from the forest — much more dynamic water flow…"

        Streamwalker said, "This way — the path gets softer soon. Watch your footing."
